      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we first studied the atom (<htcite0>), we observed that our understanding of it has evolved over time. In general terms, we can say that we have always sought something indivisible.\n\nAs knowledge advanced, we moved from the idea of an indivisible atom to understanding it as a structure made up of elementary particles.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2fd2e872-c5d8-4f1b-91dc-97df40597c4e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Evolution of Knowledge (Atom)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: I Only Know That I Know Nothing</b><br /><br />When we have little knowledge, we may believe we hold an unquestionable truth. However, as we deepen our studies, we realize there is always more to learn.<br /><br />Have you ever had a certainty that you later abandoned after studying the subject more deeply?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_models",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Atomic Models\n\nThe first explanation of the atom we studied — the Rutherford model — proposed an atom with a solid nucleus made up of positive charges, the protons, and electrons moving around it. In that same study, we also learned that, years later, another particle was discovered in the nucleus of heavy atoms: the neutron (<htcite0>).\n\n#### Almost There\n\nThe Rutherford model explained some of the measurements observed in the atom, but not all. In other words, it was a model that still needed improvement. But what exactly did it fail to explain?\n\n#### Hydrogen\n\nTo better understand what was missing, we will study the smallest atom we know — the hydrogen atom.\n\nOur studies on the hydrogen atom show that it has the following internal structure (<htcite1>):\n- Only one proton in its nucleus;\n- One electron orbiting the nucleus.\n\nBased on what we have already studied about fractions (<htcite2>), we could represent a hydrogen atom as:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2fd2e872-c5d8-4f1b-91dc-97df40597c4e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Evolution of Knowledge (Atom)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7e5a60a0-b19d-49a4-a2c2-fd3467d98ead",
                     "text": "Jolly, W.L",
                     "page": "Hydrogen",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "17"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two Sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1 + 1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>+</mo>  <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Representation of the hydrogen atom with two components (proton and electron).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Calculation 1** shows how we can represent the atom using fractions. We can read it as follows: one hydrogen atom has two components (2/2) — one part represented by the electron orbiting the nucleus (1/2), and the other by the proton inside the nucleus (1/2).\n\nUsing the Rutherford model, we could draw it like this:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"> <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"30\"></circle> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"25\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"143\" y=\"27\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text> <text x=\"145\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Representation of hydrogen according to the Rutherford model.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "Representation of the atom according to the Rutherford model, in which there is a large positive nucleus and small electrons around it with negative charge.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In **Chart 1**, we can see that the proton, represented by the larger white circle with a positive sign (+), is much larger than the electron, the smaller orange circle with a negative sign (–).\n\nWith this information, we can now focus on something the Rutherford model could not explain.\n\n#### The Bohr Atom\n\nWhen we look at a star, we can determine exactly what it is made of by analyzing the light it emits toward us (<htcite0>).\n\nIn the laboratory, we can perform a similar experiment. By shining continuous light on a gas and observing which wavelengths are missing (because they were absorbed), we can identify the elements contained in that gas (<htcite1>).\n\n**Chart 2** shows a simplified version of the hydrogen atom spectrum, studied by Lyman, Balmer, and Paschen (<htcite2>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "27bde378-4d52-470b-8d67-1d50e1a48d36",
                     "text": "Merrill, P. W., & Wilson, O. C.",
                     "page": "pp. 20 - 21",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1934",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "20a0b1ed-87f1-4fed-bb1a-d31f863a10bc",
                     "text": "Fowler, Michael",
                     "page": "1.4: The Atomic Spectrum of Hydrogen",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "20a0b1ed-87f1-4fed-bb1a-d31f863a10bc",
                     "text": "Fowler, Michael",
                     "page": "1.4: The Atomic Spectrum of Hydrogen",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
