               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg viewbox=\"0 0 800 200\"><rect width=\"800\" height=\"180\" fill=\"#0f172a\"/><text x=\"400\" y=\"30\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"20\" font-weight=\"bold\">The Representation of Hydrogen Atom Emission</text> <g transform=\"translate(50, 80)\"><line x1=\"0\" y1=\"70\" x2=\"700\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"#64748b\" stroke-width=\"2\"/><text x=\"0\" y=\"80\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#94a3b8\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\">1</text><text x=\"80\" y=\"80\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#94a3b8\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\">90</text><text x=\"115\" y=\"80\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#94a3b8\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\">130</text><text x=\"165\" y=\"80\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#94a3b8\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\">365</text><text x=\"518\" y=\"80\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#94a3b8\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\">700</text><text x=\"590\" y=\"80\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#94a3b8\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\">820</text><text x=\"350\" y=\"80\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#94a3b8\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\">Comprimento de onda (nm)</text><text x=\"100\" y=\"0\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#fbbf24\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"bold\">Lyman</text><text x=\"200\" y=\"0\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#34d399\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"bold\">Balmer</text><text x=\"600\" y=\"0\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#c084fc\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"bold\">Paschen</text><rect x=\"175\" y=\"15\" width=\"350\" height=\"40\" fill=\"url(#visibleGradient)\" opacity=\"0.3\"/> <text x=\"350\" y=\"0\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\" font-family=\"Arial, sans-serif\" font-size=\"10\">Luz visível</text><line x1=\"91\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"91\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#fbbf24\" stroke-width=\"1\"/><line x1=\"93\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"93\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#fbbf24\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><line x1=\"102\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"102\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#fbbf24\" stroke-width=\"1\"/> <line x1=\"175\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"175\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"2.0\"/><line x1=\"180\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"180\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"3.0\"/><line x1=\"185\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"185\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"3.0\"/><line x1=\"190\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"190\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"3.0\"/><line x1=\"200\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"200\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/> <line x1=\"224\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"224\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"274\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"274\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"455\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"455\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#22c55e\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/> <line x1=\"600\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"600\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"3.0\"/> <line x1=\"605\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"605\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"3.0\"/><line x1=\"609\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"609\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"612\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"612\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"620\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"620\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"630\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"630\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"650\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"650\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"675\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"675\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#c084fc\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><defs><linearGradient id=\"visibleGradient\" x1=\"0%\" y1=\"0%\" x2=\"100%\" y2=\"0%\"><stop offset=\"0%\" stop-color=\"#8b5cf6\"/><stop offset=\"20%\" stop-color=\"#3b82f6\"/><stop offset=\"40%\" stop-color=\"#22c55e\"/><stop offset=\"60%\" stop-color=\"#eab308\"/><stop offset=\"80%\" stop-color=\"#f97316\"/><stop offset=\"100%\" stop-color=\"#ef4444\"/></linearGradient></defs></svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 2</b>: Spectrum of the hydrogen atom.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The spectrum is made up of vertical lines spaced according to the measurements taken.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The absence of lines covering the entire image, as seen in **Chart 2**, led Bohr to refine the atomic model proposed by Rutherford.\n\nAccording to Bohr, electrons cannot move freely around the nucleus; instead, they move only in well-defined orbits.\n\nThey shift to larger orbits when they absorb energy (light) and return to smaller orbits when they emit light (<htcite0>).\n\n**Chart 3** shows Bohr’s model of the hydrogen atom. In this representation, the nucleus is colored yellow to distinguish it from the possible electron orbits.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c72c0fc7-eb03-46ab-ac97-16e6e849e4af",
                     "text": "The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica",
                     "page": "Bohr Atom",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "15"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"> <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"46\"></circle> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"30\"></circle> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"20\" fill=\"#FFFF00\"></circle> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"26\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"143\" y=\"27\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text> <text x=\"145\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 3</b>: Representation of hydrogen according to the Bohr model.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_partial",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Expanding Knowledge\n\nWhen we collide particles into each other, we can understand how matter is constituted (**Figure 1**). In addition to new discoveries, this also allows us to confirm theoretical predictions—among them, the fact that protons and neutrons have internal particles (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b2598dc1-391e-4598-97eb-3bb358d2ade3",
                     "text": "Cian O'Luanaigh",
                     "page": "50 years of quarks",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "1",
                        "day": "17"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4bcebe85-7913-45e0-9e6d-5e4d5c1f82bd",
                     "text": "CERN",
                     "page": "Recreating Big Bang matter on Earth",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgALICE\" src=\"images/CERN/2ALICEimages.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgALICE', '0%')\" /><b>Figure 1</b>: Particles produced during the collision of protons. © CERN. (<htcite0>). </p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1a21963e-5a89-4c1d-8448-e8e80f913f76",
                     "text": "Jacquemod, Melissa Marie",
                     "page": "CERN",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2017",
                        "month": "4",
                        "day": "24"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The evolution of our knowledge about the proton has not stopped since its discovery (<htcite0>). Nowadays, we know that inside protons there are three particles we call quarks, which, like electrons, are fundamental particles.\n\nThe quarks inside protons, in turn, are classified into two types: up quarks and down quarks. In the case of the proton, we know it has two up quarks and one down quark (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d19a84ff-15e1-44a7-a040-e4af4d7b57b3",
                     "text": "Perez, E., & Rizvi, E.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2012",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c5b375ee-0386-48f4-8249-88340c4244f1",
                     "text": "Ball, R. D. et al",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Representation</b><br /><br />We began our study of the hydrogen atom with two particles and separated them into two groups (1/2), which, when added together, return to the total atom (1).<br /><br />We discovered that the proton has three elementary particles inside it, known as quarks. That is, hydrogen would have at least four fundamental particles.<br /><br />How can we represent all these elementary particles using fractions?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_visual",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Representing\n\nOnce again, we will use a sheet of paper that will be divided to represent each fundamental particle, in order to understand fractions and how they relate to divisions.\n\nLet’s begin by representing **Calculation 1** as if it were a divided sheet: the left side will represent the electron and the right side the proton — just as we did in the previous text (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e6850f30-71aa-43c3-96b8-c47a81eedcb1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Dividing Again",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"sequenceNum\" class=\"tableTen\"><tr><th>electron</th><th>proton</th></tr><tr><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td><td style=\"height: 300px;\"></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Sheet divided to represent the electron and the proton.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "As we have seen, the proton contains three internal particles called quarks. Visually, we can infer that the right side of the sheet (the proton) must be divided into three equal parts:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"sequenceNum\" class=\"tableTen\"><tr><th>electron</th><th>proton</th></tr><tr><td style=\"height: 300px;\" rowspan=\"3\"></td><td><i>quark up</i></td></tr> <tr><td><i>quark up</i></td></tr> <tr><td><i>quark down</i></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 2</b>: Sheet divided to represent the electron and the proton with their quarks visible.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Before proceeding with the calculations involving the quarks, it is important to note that although the divided sheets may give the impression that electrons are larger than protons, when we talk about particle size, what truly matters is the Bohr model, shown in **Chart 3**.\n\nNow we can move on to representing them through fractions.\n\n#### Quarks in the Proton\n\nIf we were to work only with the proton and its quarks in isolation, we could represent the three quarks (temporarily ignoring the fact that there are two *up* quarks and one *down* quark) as follows:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1 + 1 + 1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Representation of the proton with three quarks.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Quarks and Protons in the Atom\n\n**Calculation 2** shows how the internal division of the proton would look, but we must remember that, in reality, it represents half (1/2) of the hydrogen atom. Once again, we will refer to a concept from the previous text (<htcite0>) to achieve a more precise approximation.\n\nThis time, instead of assuming the proton represents the whole (1), we will treat it as only half of the atom (1/2). Thus, we multiply both the numerator and the denominator by (3/3):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e6850f30-71aa-43c3-96b8-c47a81eedcb1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Dividing Again",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac mathsize=\"big\"> <mrow> <mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>(</mn> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mn>)</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>3 × 1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3 × 2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac></math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 3</b>: Division of the half into three parts.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_summing",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Reassembling the Whole\n\nAfter seeing how we separated the particles of atoms, we now need to understand how to regroup all these particles to form a single atom again.\n\nUnlike in previous texts, where we added values that had been evenly divided, this time we have half of a sheet representing an electron (1/2) and another half representing three quarks inside the proton (3/6).\n\nThis situation leads us to perform the addition in a slightly different way than simply adding the numerators (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0836cb37-3574-4ca8-9efa-d3fd158b0805",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Fractions",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: What now?</b><br /><br />We want to add the parts (1/2 and 3/6) in order to form a single atom (1).<br /><br />How can we obtain the whole from two different fractions?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "As we have studied, the total quantity in fractions is represented by the denominator — the lower part of the fraction (<htcite0>).\n\nConnecting this concept with the idea that multiplication is the repetitive addition of equal elements (<htcite1>), we can solve the sum of “different” elements to obtain the whole.\n\n#### Step by Step\n\nThe first step in performing the sum is to write exactly what we want to add.\n\nIn our example, we want to add the elements of the electrosphere — the region where the electrons are located — with the elements of the nucleus, to obtain the hydrogen atom:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two Sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the Same Numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>O átomo</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>eletrosfera</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>núcleo</mn></math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 4</b>: Representation of the sum of the electrosphere and the nucleus</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In **Calculation 1**, the atom represents the total (1). The electrosphere was defined as half of the atom (1/2), and the nucleus of the hydrogen atom — the other half — was identified as a single proton with three quarks (3/6).",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 5</b>: Representation of the elements of the hydrogen atom.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In the next step, we must remember that whenever reactions occur in matter, matter is conserved (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). This means that if we perform an operation on the right-hand side, we must also perform it on the left-hand side.\n\nThus, we first rebuild the whole, remembering that the initial total contained two parts (2/2), leaving the discovery of the quarks (3/6) for the next stage. So, we multiply **Calculation 5** by 2:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "68227419-2430-4359-b902-f6cf87b8941d",
                     "text": "Holmes, F. L.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1985",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b9866acb-fde8-4fcb-b54d-ee7c481cc9e7",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Shared Origin",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>2 × 1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>2 × 1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2 × 3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>2 × 1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac>  <mn>× 1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2 × 3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>2</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 6</b>: Representation of the elements of the hydrogen atom.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To reach the part that constitutes the three quarks, we consider that the other half (1/2) internally contained three additional parts, leading us to a total of 6/6.\n\nMultiplying both sides by 6, we get:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center> <center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>6 × 2</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>6 × 1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>6 × 6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center> <center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>6 × 2</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>6 × 1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>×</mo> <mn>6</mn> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>12</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>6</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>6</mn> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>12</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>12</mn> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 7</b>: Representation of the summed elements.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Calculation 7** shows that, starting from the parts, we were able to return to the whole atom.\n\nTo transform it back into 1, we multiply both sides by (1/12):",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>12</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>12</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 8</b>: Returning to the total.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Finally, we return to our initial stage: a single atom represented through fractions.\n\n### Simplification Is Not Omission\n\nIn different situations in life, we often have so many tasks that we simply memorize formulas and substitute numbers without truly understanding the whole.\n\nFor example, let’s look at **Formula 1** provided by *Wolfran Mathworld* (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0836cb37-3574-4ca8-9efa-d3fd158b0805",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Fractions",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>a</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>b</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>c</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>d</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>(a × d) + (b × c)</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>(b × d)</mn><mrow> </mfrac></math></center></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1</b>: Soma de frações.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Now, substituting the values:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>(1 × 6) + (2 × 3)</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2 × 6</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>6 + 6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>12</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </math></center></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 9</b>: Sum of Fractions Using Formula 1.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 4: Same Result</b><br /><br />If, by using a formula, we get the same result as when doing the process step by step, why do we need to go through the steps?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Formulas are a way to summarize our understanding of a phenomenon.\n\nHowever, if the phenomenon itself is not understood, formulas become nothing more than groups of letters and symbols without meaning.\n\nAll the steps we performed from **Calculation 1** through **Calculation 8** are represented in **Calculation 9**.\n\nTherefore, the fact that both yield the same result is not a coincidence.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we studied the hydrogen atom in more depth and saw how, through fractions, we can represent the particles that make up an atom and, from them, reconstruct the complete whole.\n\nWe also learned that, in studying nature, everything observed can be summarized in a formula. However, if we don’t understand what we’re studying, we’ll hardly be able to formulate a coherent explanation for the phenomenon.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
